nt Achievements = }}
'''Kamo no Tadayuki''' (賀茂 忠行) was a {{ill|noble|ja|貴族|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/noble|qq=}} and {{ill|Onmyōji|ja|陰陽家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōji|qq=}} active during the {{ill|Early Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Early Heian period|qq=}} to {{ill|Mid Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mid Heian period|qq=}}. He is best known as the mentor of {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe no Seimei|qq=}}. His father was either {{ill|Kamo no Enjin|ja|賀茂江人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo no Enjin|qq=}} or {{ill|Kamo no Mineo|ja|賀茂峯雄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo no Mineo|qq=}}. He held the court Rank of Junior Fifth Rank and served as Assistant Governor of Tanba.
== Achievements ==
Kamo no Tadayuki excelled in the art of {{ill|divination|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/divination|qq=}}, earning unwavering trust from the {{ill|Emperor of Japan|ja|天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor of Japan|qq=}}. He was particularly renowned for his skill in ''{{ill|Shikuku|ja|射覆|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikuku|qq=}}'' (divining the contents of a concealed object). One notable incident, recorded in the {{ill|Konjaku Monogatari|ja|今昔物語集|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konjaku Monogatari|qq=}}, describes how he correctly identified a crystal rosary wrapped in red cord hidden in an octagonal box, astonishing the emperor and earning widespread acclaim.
== Role in Onmyōdō History ==
Tadayuki's contributions to {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōdō|qq=}} were pivotal. Prior to his time, the three branches of Onmyōdō—{{ill|Astronomy|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Astronomy|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmondō (astrology)|qq=}}, {{ill|Calendar-making|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Calendar-making|13=User:Immanuelle/Rekidō|qq=}}, and {{ill|Onmyōdō|lt=Onmyōdō proper|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōdō|qq=}}—were practiced separately by specialized experts. However, Tadayuki, originally a {{ill|calendar scholar|ja|暦家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/calendar scholar|qq=}}, transcended these divisions, uniting the disciplines under the leadership of the {{ill|Kamo clan|ja|賀茂氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo clan|qq=}}. This consolidation laid the groundwork for the future dominance of the Kamo and {{ill|Abe clan|ja|安倍氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe clan|qq=}} in Onmyōdō.
== Historical Context ==
The suspension of the {{ill|Kentōshi|ja|遣唐使|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kentōshi|qq=}} missions in the 6th year of Kanpyō (894) under {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugawara no Michizane|qq=}} meant that no new knowledge on {{ill|Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|ja|陰陽五行思想|1=Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|1=Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|qq=}} was being imported from the continent. This restriction fostered an environment where Onmyōdō practices became increasingly reliant on existing knowledge. The Kamo clan took advantage of this situation to innovate, blending {{ill|Daoist|ja|道教|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daoist|qq=}} rituals with elements of {{ill|Esoteric Buddhism|ja|密教|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Esoteric Buddhism|qq=}}. This shift from purely technical practices to religious and ritualistic functions revitalized the declining discipline.
== Appearances in Literature and Media ==
Tadayuki is featured prominently in legends such as: * ''Konjaku Monogatari'': Narratives detail his encounters with {{ill|Hyakki Yagyō|ja|百鬼夜行|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hyakki Yagyō|qq=}} and his mentorship of Abe no Seimei. * He is depicted in modern adaptations such as: ** ''{{ill|Onmyōji☆Abe Seimei: Royal Capital Mystical Tales|ja|陰陽師☆安倍晴明〜王都妖奇譚〜|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōji☆Abe Seimei: Royal Capital Mystical Tales|qq=}}'' (2002, Fuji TV), played by {{ill|Yasutaka Tsutsui|ja|筒井康隆|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasutaka Tsutsui|qq=}}. ** ''{{ill|Neko Neko Nihonshi|ja|ねこねこ日本史|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Neko Neko Nihonshi|qq=}}'' (2018, NHK), voiced by {{ill|Yūsuke Shirai|ja|白井悠介|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yūsuke Shirai|qq=}}.
