Tadayuki's contributions to [[:en:Onmyōdō|Onmyōdō]] were pivotal. Prior to his time, the three branches of Onmyōdō—{{ill|Astronomy|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Astronomy|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmondō (astrology)|qq=}}, {{ill|Calendar-making|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Calendar-making|13=User:Immanuelle/Rekidō|qq=}}, and [[:en:Onmyōdō|Onmyōdō proper]]—were practiced separately by specialized experts. However, Tadayuki, originally a {{ill|Rekidō|lt=Rekidō|lt=Calendar scholar|ja|暦家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/calendar scholar|qq=}}, transcended these divisions, uniting the disciplines under the leadership of the {{ill|Kamo clan|ja|賀茂氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo clan|qq=}}. This consolidation laid the groundwork for the future dominance of the Kamo and {{ill|Abe clan|ja|安倍氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe clan|qq=}} in Onmyōdō.
== Historical Context ==
The suspension of the [[:en:Japanese missions to Tang China|Kentōshi]] missions in the 6th year of Kanpyō (894) under {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugawara no Michizane|qq=}} meant that no new knowledge on {{ill|Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|ja|陰陽五行思想|1=Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|1=Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|qq=}} was being imported from the continent. This restriction fostered an environment where Onmyōdō practices became increasingly reliant on existing knowledge. The Kamo clan took advantage of this situation to innovate, blending [[:en:Taoism|Daoist]] rituals with elements of [[:en:Mikkyō|Esoteric Buddhism]]. This shift from purely technical practices to religious and ritualistic functions revitalized the declining discipline.
== Appearances in Literature and Media ==
Tadayuki is featured prominently in legends such as: * ''Konjaku Monogatari'': Narratives detail his encounters with [[:en:Hyakki Yagyō|Hyakki Yagyō]] and his mentorship of Abe no Seimei. * He is depicted in modern adaptations such as: ** ''{{ill|Onmyōji☆Abe Seimei: Royal Capital Mystical Tales|ja|陰陽師☆安倍晴明〜王都妖奇譚〜|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōji☆Abe Seimei: Royal Capital Mystical Tales|qq=}}'' (2002, Fuji TV), played by [[:en:Yasutaka Tsutsui|Yasutaka Tsutsui]]. ** ''{{ill|Neko Neko Nihonshi|ja|ねこねこ日本史|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Neko Neko Nihonshi|qq=}}'' (2018, NHK), voiced by [[:en:Yusuke Shirai|Yūsuke Shirai]].
